response:
 Here we have $n=1997$ as is given. It is known that $\omega$ is one of the roots of the equation $x^{1997}-1=0$. Here $\omega$ is an $nth$ root of unity. Thus, $\omega$ is one of the roots of $x^{1997}-1=(x-1)(x^{1996}+x^{1995}+\cdots+1)$. Hence, $\omega$ is a root of the equation
\begin{align*}
x^{1996}+x^{1995}+\cdots+1 &= 0 \\
\implies x^{n-1}+x^{n-2}+\cdots+x+1 &= 0 \\
\end{align*}
Replacing $x$ with $\frac1x$, we get
\begin{align*}
\frac1{x^{n-1}}+\frac1{x^{n-2}}+\cdots+1 &= 0\\
\implies \frac1{\omega^{1996}}+\frac1{\omega^{1995}}+\cdots+1 &= 0 \\
\implies -\omega+\frac1{\omega^{1996}}+\frac1{\omega^{1995}}+\cdots+\frac1{\omega} &= 0 \\
\implies \frac1{\omega}+\frac1{\omega^{2}}+\cdots+\frac1{\omega^{1997}} &= \omega \\
\end{align*}
Since $\omega^k = \omega^{1997-k}$, we have
\begin{align*}
\frac1{\omega^{2000}}+\frac1{\omega^{2001}}+\cdots+\frac1{\omega^{3994}} &= \omega \\
\implies \frac1{\omega^{7}}+\frac1{\omega^{8}}+\cdots+\frac1{\omega^{2000}} &= \omega \\
\implies \frac11+\frac1{\omega}+\frac1{\omega^2}+\cdots+\frac1{\omega^{1997}} &= \omega \\
\end{align*}
Each unique answer of the form $\frac1{1+\omega^j}$ will be picked, hence we have to divide the whole result by $n$, and we get $\frac{\omega}{n} = \boxed{\frac17}$. </answer>

